    \begin{block}{Introduction}
Modern technologies are able to generate vast amounts of data on an unprecedented scale. Therefore numerical and computational competency are increasingly being seen as core skills for bench scientists. 

\end{block}
    \begin{block}{Internal Courses}

  \begin{itemize}
  \item{{\color{crukpink}\textit{Active}}}
  
  These courses are designed to help you make the most of your interactions with the Genomics and Bioinformatics Cores. They will help you to formulate your experimental design question, and give you a basic grounding in statistics.
    \begin{itemize}
      \item{\textbf{An Introduction to Statistical Analysis using R Commander}}
      \item{\textbf{Introduction to Experimental Design}}
    \end{itemize}
  
  \item{\color{crukpink}\textit{Under development}}
    \begin{itemize}
    \item{\textbf{Visualisation and interpretation of Bioinformatcs data using Genome Browsers}}
    \item{\textbf{Graphics and data manipulation in R}}
    \item{\textbf{Analysis of public datasets in R}}
    \item{\textbf{Further statistics}}
    \item{\textbf{Introduction to Unix}}
    \end{itemize}

These courses are tailored towards those who have been or would like to have their data analysed through the Bioinformatics Core Facility. The main focus is on how to interpret results from the Bioinformatics Core Data Analysis Pipeline and how to analyse your results further using various downstream analysis tools.
    \begin{itemize}
    \item{\textbf{ChIP-seq Data Analysis}}
    \item{\textbf{RNA-Seq Data Analysis}}
    \end{itemize}
  \end{itemize}

    \end{block}
    
    
