        {\color{crukpink}{\textit{"To consult the statistician after an experiment is finished is often merely to ask him to conduct a post mortem examination. He can perhaps say what the experiment died of." - R.A. Fisher}}}
        
This quote by Fisher sums up why experimental design is a crucial part of the experimental process. For this reason, our training course on Experimental Design is \textbf{compulsory} for all new PhD students. The course is also run regularly for other researchers at C.I.\\


Statistics teaching is done using the R Commander GUI; a user-friendly way of doing statistical analysis in R (\cite{Rcmdr}). Therefore the focus of this training is on the statistical concepts, rather than wrestling with the R language. In this course we introduce the basics of statistics and hypothesis testing. The Bioinformatics Core at Cambridge Research Institute employs statisticians to help researchers at the institute with the statistical aspects of their studies. Whilst we are always happy to do an analysis for you, we are also happy to support you if you choose to run the analysis yourself. Please get in touch if you have any questions or require our support, or come along to our Wednesday afternoon Statistics Clinic - {\color{crukpink}{\tt cristatsclinic@cruk.cam.ac.uk}}. \vspace{1cm}

Material from our experimental design and statistics courses are available on Sharepoint. \vspace{1cm}

